Unsolved Practical:  Create a simple JavaScript program that simulates a basic personal information form. The program should do the following:
•	Declare variables to store your name, age, favorite color, and a list of your favorite hobbies.
•	Use appropriate data types for each variable.
•	Log all the variables to the console.
•	Display a summary of the information on the webpage using document.write.
•	Include comments to explain each part of the code

// Declare variables to store personal information

// Name (string)
let name = "John Doe";

// Age (number)
let age = 30;

// Favorite color (string)
let favoriteColor = "Blue";

// Favorite hobbies (array)
let favoriteHobbies = ["Reading", "Hiking", "Coding"];

// Log variables to the console
console.log("Name:", name);
console.log("Age:", age);
console.log("Favorite Color:", favoriteColor);
console.log("Favorite Hobbies:", favoriteHobbies);

// Display summary on webpage using document.write
document.write("<h1>Personal Information</h1>");
document.write("<p>Name: " + name + "</p>");
document.write("<p>Age: " + age + "</p>");
document.write("<p>Favorite Color: " + favoriteColor + "</p>");
document.write("<p>Favorite Hobbies: " + favoriteHobbies.join(", ") + "</p>");



Explanation:

1. Variable declarations:
    - name: string (text)
    - age: number (integer)
    - favoriteColor: string (text)
    - favoriteHobbies: array (list of strings)

2. Logging variables to the console:
    - console.log() function displays values in browser's console

3. Displaying summary on webpage:
    - document.write() function writes HTML content to webpage
    - Concatenation (+) combines strings and variables
    - join() method converts array to comma-separated string
